searchable_info.topic: Adding documents to your Cart on TexasFile
searchable_info.description: My Cart is a feature on TexasFile allowing users to purchase and download multiple documents in a single zip file including an Excel index report. To add docs to your Cart, click the Cart icon in search results then visit the Cart page.

searchable_info.topic: Looking for information about a Texas Driver's License?
searchable_info.description: TexasFile does not provide information about driver's licenses. For more information, contact the Texas Department of Public Safety using the link below.
Criminal records are not available on TexasFile. To locate this information, contact the District Clerk's office by using our County Directory below.
Marriage Certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a death certificate, contact the County Clerk's office using our County Directory below.
Birth Certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a birth certificate, contact the County Clerk's office by using our County Directory below.
TexasFile does not provide access to District Clerk or District Court records. Please contact the District Clerk's office by using our County Directory below.

Zoning is the right of a municipality to regulate and determine the compatible character and use
of property.
Changing your username requires TexasFile customer service assistance. Please contact us using the link below.
Divorce decrees are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a divorce decree, contact the County Clerk's office by using our County Directory below.

A credit card is needed to purchase documents on TexasFile. The full credit card number will not be stored on TexasFile, only the last 4 digits of the credit card and expiration date. To add a credit card, please click on the link below.

Plat (of Survey) is a map of land made by a surveyor showing boundary lines, buildings, and
other improvements on the land.
Ingress is the right to enter a tract of land. Often used interchangeably with "access."

Joint Tenancy is an estate where two or more persons hold real estate jointly for life, the
survivors to take the interest of the one who dies.

searchable_info.topic: Looking for a copy of your home survey?
searchable_info.description: Residential home surveys are typically not recorded in the County Clerk's Office and not available on TexasFile. The title agent that closed your real estate transaction may have a copy of your survey. Use the link below to locate a title agent.

searchable_info.topic: What is an Abstract of Title?
searchable_info.description: An Abstract of Title is compilation of all the recorded documents relating to a parcel of land.
Judgment Lien - See "Abstract of Judgment"

Tax Lien is the lien which is imposed upon real estate by operation of law which secures the
payment of real estate taxes.

Will is a written document providing for the distribution of property owned by a person after his
or her death.
An Access is the right to enter and leave a tract of land from a public way. It can include the right to enter and leave over the lands of another.

Cloud on Title is an outstanding claim or encumbrance which adversely affects the
marketability of title.
Death Certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a death certificate, contact the County Clerk's office using our County Directory below.
Judgment is a decree of a court.

Warranty is a promise by the grantor of real property that he or she is the owner and will be
responsible to the buyer if title is other than represented.

searchable_info.topic: What is an Abstract of Judgment?
searchable_info.description: An Abstract of Judgment is a lien created by a statutory filing of a court judgment in the real property records. This lien, commonly referred to as an AJ (in Texas), attaches to all nonexempt real property of the person or entity that the judgment was against.
Accretion is the slow build-up of lands by natural forces such as wind or water.
Acknowledgment is a formal declaration before an authorized officer (usually a notary public) by a person who has executed an instrument that such execution is the individual's act.
An acre is a tract of land 208.71 feet square and containing 43,560 square feet of land.

An Administrator is a person appointed by a probate court to settle the estate of an individual that
has died. The term is "administratrix" if such person is a woman.

Adverse Possession is a claim made against the lands of another by virtue of open and notorious
possession of said lands by the claimant.
An Affiant is one who swears to or affirms the statement in an affidavit.

Affirmative Coverage are provisions in policies by which the insurer affirmatively insures
against loss due to specific risks generally not covered by policies.
Air Rights is the right to ownership of everything above the physical surface of the land.

searchable_info.topic: What is an All Inclusive Rate?
searchable_info.description:
An All Inclusive Rate is the system of quoting rates for insurance where the stated rate includes the
cost of title search, title examination, closing the transaction and the policy. This system is in
contrast with the system which quotes the rate charged for the policy only. The cost of search
and examination in this latter system is extra.

An Appraisal is an estimate of value of property from analysis of facts about the property; an
opinion of value.

Appurtenances are rights which pass with the title to the land itself. These rights may affect
other lands; e.g., an appropriate access easement over adjoining land.

An Assessment is the imposition of a tax, charge or levy, usually according to established rates by a
taxing authority or a unit or subdivision governing authority.

An Assignment is a transfer of (or the document transferring) a right and/or interest in land. Used
often in transferring interests of a mortgagee or lessee.

Condition or Conditions is a A proviso in a deed or will that, upon the happening or failure to
happen of a certain event, limits, enlarges, changes or terminates the title of the purchaser or
devisee.

Bankruptcy is a federal court proceeding in which debtors may be relieved of liability for their
debts after surrender of their assets to a court appointed trustee.
Bill of Sale is a written document that transfers title to personal property.

Bond is (1) An insurance agreement under which one party becomes surety to pay, within stated
limits, financial loss caused to another by specified acts or defaults of a third party. (2) An
interest bearing security evidencing a long-term debt, issued by a government or corporation,
and sometimes secured by a lien on property.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Chain of Title
searchable_info.description:
Chain of Title is a term applied to the past series of transactions and documents affecting the
title to a particular parcel of land.

Condominium is a system of individual fee ownership of units in a multi-unit structure,
combined with joint ownership of common areas of the structure and land.

Conditions and Restrictions are set of rules, limitations and restrictions established by a
developer or homeowners association that governs the use of real estate. Includes penalties for
failure to comply.

Community Property is a category of property, existing in some states, in which all property
(except property specifically acquired by husband or wife a separate property) acquired by a
husband and wife, or either, during marriage, is owned in common by the husband and wife.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Contract of Deed?
searchable_info.description:
Contract of Deed is an agreement to sell and purchase under which title is held as security by
the seller until such time as the required payments to the seller have been completed.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Contract of Sale?
searchable_info.description:
Contract of Sale is an agreement by one person to buy and another person to sell a specified parcel
of land at a specified price.

Conveyance is - (1) A document which transfers an interest in real property from one person to
another; e.g., a deed. (2) The act of executing and delivering a deed or mortgage.

Condominium Declaration is the document which establishes a condominium and describes
the most important property rights of the unit owners. Special statutes in each state prescribe the
contents of this document, known in some states as a "master deed."

Condemnation is (1) The lawful taking of private land for public use by a government under its
right of eminent domain. (2) A declaration by a governmental agency that a building is unfit for
use.
Convey is the act of deeding or transferring title to another

Dedication is the granting of land by the owner for some public use and its acceptance for such
use by authorized public officials.

Deed is a written instrument duly executed and delivered by which the title to land is transferred
from one person to another.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Deed in Lieu?
searchable_info.description:
Deed in Lieu is short for Deed in Lieu of Foreclosure, this conveys title to the lender when the
borrower is in default and wants to avoid foreclosure.

Deed of Trust is a conveyance of a land title by a maker of a note (the debtor) to a third party, a
trustee, as collateral security for the payment of the note with the condition that the trustee shall
reconvey the title to the debtor upon payment of the note, and with power in the trustee to sell
the land and pay the note in the event of a default on the part of the debtor.
Defect - A blemish, imperfection or deficiency. A defective title is one that is irregular and
faulty.

Deficiency of Judgment is a judgment against a person liable for the debt secured by a mortgage
in an amount by which the funds derived from a foreclosure or trustee's sale are less than the
amount due on the debt.

Easement is a privilege or right of use or enjoyment which one person may have in the lands of
another; for example, a right of way to install, operate, and maintain utility lines.

Encroachment is the intrusion of any improvement partly or entirely on the land of another or
into an easement or setback area.
Estate is a person's possessions. The extent of a person's interest in real property.

Earnest Money is an advanced payment of part of the purchase price made by a purchaser as
evidence of good faith.

Cul-de-Sac is the terminus of a street or alley. Usually laid out by modern engineers to provide
a circular turnaround for vehicles.

Cutesy is a husband's life estate in the property of his deceased wife. By statute in most states,
it is a life estate in one third of the land she owned during their marriage. Curtesy has been
abolished by statute in some states.
Debt is an amount owed to another.
Devise is the disposition of property by will.
Devisee is the person to whom property is given by a will.
Executor is a person named in a will to administer the estate. Executrix is the feminine form.

Exclusions are those general matters affecting title to real property excluded from coverage of a
title insurance policy.

Dower is an estate for life to which a married woman by statute is entitled on the death of her
husband.

Fannie Mae is the Federal National Mortgage Association (also FNMA) is a private corporation,
federally chartered to provide financial products and services that increase the availability and
affordability of housing by purchasing mortgage loans.

Financing Statement is a document filed in the Real Property Records or with the Secretary of
State to create a security interest in the title to personal property.

Foreclosure is the legal process by which a mortgagor of real property is deprived of interest in that
property due to failure to pay the loan or comply with terms and conditions of the mortgage.

Forfeiture of Title is a provision in a deed creating a condition which will cause title to be passed
to another should certain circumstances occur.

searchable_info.topic: What is a General Warranty Deed?
searchable_info.description:
General Warranty Deed is a deed containing a covenant whereby the seller agrees to protect
the buyer against being dispossessed because of any adverse claim against the land.

Heir is the person who, at the death of the owner of land, is entitled to the land if the owner has
died without a will or if part or all of a will is ineffective.

Hiatus is a gap or space unintentionally left, when attempting to describe adjoining parcels of
land. The same as a vacancy.

Homeowners' Association is a nonprofit association that manages the common areas of a
planned unit development (PUD) or condominium project.

Homestead (Exemption) is a person's dwelling and that part of the land which is contiguous to
the dwelling. Many states by statute give special privileges to such lands, such as exemptions
from remedies of creditors.

Improvements are those additions to raw lands tending to increase value, such as buildings,
streets, sewer, etc.

Indemnity Agreement is an agreement by the maker of the document to pay up to the limit
stated for any loss due to the contingency stated in the agreement.

Inchoate Curtesy is the imperfect interest which the law gives a husband in the lands of his
wife. This is an interest which upon the death of the wife may ripen into possession and use.
Most states have abolished curtesy rights.

Guardian is one appointed by the court to administer the affairs of an individual not capable of
administering his or her own affairs.
Grantor is a person who, by a written instrument, transfers to another an interest in land.

Flood Insurance is Insurance that compensates for physical property damage resulting from
flooding. It is required for properties located in federally designated flood areas.
Flood Certification- This determines whether land or a building is located within a Special Flood Hazard Area for purposes of flood insurance requirements under the National Flood Insurance Program.

Fixtures are any item of property so attached to real property that it becomes a part of the real
property.

FHA = The Federal Housing Administration, an agency of the federal government which insures
private loans for financing of new and existing housing and for home repairs under government
approved programs.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Fee Simple Estate?
searchable_info.description:
Fee Simple Estate is the greatest interest in a parcel of land that is possible to own. Sometimes
designated simply as "fee."

Fannie Mae (FNMA) is the Federal National Mortgage Association, which is a congressionally
chartered, shareholder-owned company that is the nations largest supplier of home mortgage
funds.

Lease is a written agreement between the property owner and a tenant that stipulates the payment
and conditions under which the tenant may possess the real estate for a specified period of time.

term: Lien Waiver or Waiver of Liens
searchable_info.topic: What is Lien Waiver or Waiver of Liens?
searchable_info.description:
Lien Waiver or Waiver of Liens is a document signed by the general contractor, each
subcontractor, an each materialman of a construction project whereby the signators waive their
right to mechanics' liens on the land involved in that particular project.

Lis Pendens is a recorded legal notice that there is litigation pending relating to the land and a
warning that anyone obtaining an interest subsequent to the date of the notice may be bound by
the judgment.

Mechanic's Lien is a lien or claim of lien allowed by statute to contractors, laborers and
material suppliers on buildings or other structures upon which work has been performed or
materials supplied.

Modification - Occasionally, a lender will agree to modify the terms of your mortgage without
requiring you to refinance. If any changes are made, it is called a modification.
Mortgage is an instrument used to encumber land as security for a debt.

Note is a written promise to pay a certain amount of money, plus interest at a specified rate, at a
certain time, and in a certain number of installments.

Partition is division of land, usually by a legal proceeding, among the parties who were
formerly co-owners.

Judicial Foreclosure is a type of foreclosure proceeding used in some states that is handled as a
civil lawsuit and conducted entirely under the auspices of a Court. Other states use non-judicial
foreclosure.

Land is the land described, specifically or by reference, and improvements affixed thereto
which by law constitute real property.
Landmark is any conspicuous object that helps establish land boundaries.

Leasehold is the right to possession and use of land for a fixed period of time. The lease is the
agreement which creates the right. The person who has the leasehold is the tenant or lessee. The
person who grants the leasehold is the lessor or landlord.

Legal Description is a property description which by law is sufficient to locate and identify the
parcel of real property on the ground.
Lien is a claim or charge on property of another for payment of some debt, obligation, or duty.

Life Estate is a grant or reservation of the right of use, occupancy and ownership for the life of
an individual.
Link is a term of land measurement being 1/100th of a chain or 66/100ths of a foot.

Lot is a part of a subdivision or block having fixed boundaries ascertainable by reference to a
plat or survey.
M.E.R.S = Mortgage Electronic Registration System.

Metes and Bounds is a description of a parcel of land by describing the boundary lines in length
and direction.

Monument of Survey are visible marks or indications left on natural or other objects indicating
the lines and boundaries of a survey. May be posts, pillars, stones, cairns, and other such
objects. May also be fixed natural objects, blazed trees, roads and even a water course.

Mortgagee is the lender who provides the money for the mortgage and to whom the mortgage is
given.
Notary is one authorized to take acknowledgments. See "Acknowledgment."
Ownership is the right to possess and use property to the exclusion of others.
Personal Property is any property that is not real property.

Planned Unit Development (PUD) is a project consisting of individually owned parcels of land
together with common areas and facilities that are owned by an association of which the owners
of all the parcels are members.

Power of Attorney is an instrument in writing by which one person, the principal, authorizes
another, the attorney-in-fact, to act in the specific actions described in the instrument.

Probate is a legal procedure in which the validity and probity of a document, such as a will, is
proven.

Promissory Note is a written promise to pay or repay a specified sum of money at a stated time,
or on demand, to a named person. In addition to the payment of principal, a promissory note
usually provides for the payment of interest.
Public Records are records which by law impart constructive notice of matters relating to land.

Quitclaim is a deed which transfers whatever interest the maker of the deed may have in the
particular parcel of land.
Receipts can be downloaded for both Funds(Credit) that have been added, which would include the sales tax and Documents(Activity) that have been purchased

Residential Real Property is Real Property that is improved and is designed principally for
occupancy by one to four families. The term includes an individual unit of a condominium or
cooperative.

Record Title - The aspects of a title which appear in the public records as distinguished from
unrecorded title aspects and interests.

Recorder is the public official who keeps records of transactions that affect real property in the
area. Sometimes known as a "Registrar of Deeds" or "County Clerk."

Recording is the noting in the designated public office of the details of a properly executed
legal document such as a deed or mortgage, thereby making it a part of the public record, and
thus by law imparting constructive notice of that document to the public.

Release is a document form the mortgagee or trustee of a deed of trust which releases specific
property from the lien of the mortgage or deed of trust.

Restrictions is a provision in a deed or will or in a Declaration of Condition, Reservations and
Restrictions which limits in some way the right to use land or convey its title. Examples are
building setback lines and limitations to residential uses.

searchable_info.topic: What is Right of Ingress or Egress?
searchable_info.description: Right of Ingress or Egress is the right to enter or leave designated premises.

Right of Survivorship = In joint tenancy, the right of survivors to acquire the interest of a
deceased joint tenant.
Right of Way is the right which one has to pass across the lands of another. An easement.

Riparian is pertaining to the banks of a watercourse. The owner of land adjacent to a
watercourse is called a riparian owner and the rights of the riparian owner related to that
watercourse are called riparian rights.

searchable_info.topic: What is Section or Sections of Land?
searchable_info.description: Section or Sections of Land is a parcel of land comprising one square mile or 640 acres.

Set Back Lines are those lines which delineate the required distances for the location of
structures in relation to the perimeter of the property.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Special Warranty Deed?
searchable_info.description:
Special Warranty Deed is a deed containing a covenant whereby the seller agrees to protect the
buyer against being dispossessed because of any adverse claims to the land by the seller, or
anyone claiming through the seller.
Subdivision is a tract of land surveyed and divided into lots for purposes of sale.

Sub-Surface Right is the right of ownership to things lying beneath the physical surface of the
property.

Quiet Title is an action in a proper Court to remove record defects or possible claims of other
parties named in the action.
Real Property is land together with fixtures, improvements and appurtenances.

Reversion = Provision in conveyance by which, upon the happening of an event or contingency,
title to the land will return to the grantor or the successor in interest in the land.

searchable_info.topic: What is Tenancy by the Entirety?
searchable_info.description:
Tenancy by the Entirety is ownership by married persons where each owns the entire estate,
with the survivor taking the whole upon the others death.

Tenancy in Common is an estate or interest in land held by two or more persons, each having
equal rights of possession and enjoyment, but without any right of succession by survivorship
between the owners.

Tenant is one who has right of possession of land by any kind of title. The word tenant used
alone in modern times is used almost exclusively in the limited meaning of a tenant of a
leasehold estate.
Testament is another term for a will. Commonly referred to as last will and testament.
Testate is the estate or condition of leaving a will at death. To die testate.
Testator is a man who makes or has made a testament or will.
Testatrix is a woman who makes or has made a testament or will.
Title is the evidence of right which a person has to the ownership and possession of land.
Title Company is a company that specializes in examining and insuring titles to real estate.

Title Defect is any legal right held by others to claim property or to make demands upon the
owner.

Title Examination is the search and examination of a title to determine the conditions of the title
to be insured and to evaluate the risk to be undertaken in the issuance of a title insurance policy
or other title insurance form.

Title Insurance is insurance against loss or damage resulting from defects or failure of title to a
particular parcel of real property.

Title Search is an examination of public records, laws, and court decisions to disclose the
current facts regarding ownership of real estate.
Tract is a particular parcel of land.
Trust is a property right held by one as a fiduciary for the benefit of another.
Waiver is the voluntary and intentional relinquishment of a known right, claim or privilege.

Warranty Deed is a deed in which the grantor warrants or guarantees that indefeasible title is
being conveyed.

Title Plant is the total facilities (records, equipment, fixtures, and personnel) required to
function as a title insurance operation. Technically, the organization of official records affecting
real property into a system which allows quick and efficient recovery of title information.

Title Policy is any contract of title insurance, the form for which is prescribed by the
Commissioner.

TLTA = Texas Land Title Association, a statewide trade association representing the title
insurance industry in Texas.
Township is a division of territory six miles square, containing 36 sections or 36 square miles.

Torrens System is a governmental title registration system wherein title to land is evidenced by
a certificate of title issued by a public official known as the registrar of title.
Trustee is a person holding property in trust as a fiduciary for the benefit of another.

Underwriter is an insurance company which issues insurance policies either to the public or to
another insurer.
Vendee is a purchaser of real property under land contract. (Buyer.)
Vendor is a seller of real property under land contract. (Seller.)
Vest is to become owned by.

Tax Deed is the deed given to a purchaser at a public sale of land for non-payment of taxes. It
conveys to the purchaser only such title as the defaulting taxpayer had and does not convey
insurable title to that extent unless statutory procedures for the sale were strictly followed.

Survey is the process of measuring land to determine its size, location and physical description
and the resulting drawing or map.

Harbor Line is an arbitrary line set by authorities on navigable rivers, beyond which wharves
and other structures may note be built. Also designated as line of navigation.

Inchoate Dower is the imperfect interest which the law gives a wife in the lands of her husband.
This is an interest which upon the death of the husband may ripen into possession and use. Most
states have abolished dower rights.
Intestate is without having made a valid will or one who dies without having made a will.

Patent is a document or grant by which the federal or state government originally transferred
title to public lands to an individual. The first in the series of transfers by which title comes
down to present owners.

Range is a part of the government survey, being a strip of land six miles in width and numbered
east or west of the principal meridian.

Transfer of Ownership is any means by which the ownership of a property changes hands.
Lenders consider all of the following situations to be a transfer of ownership: the purchase of a
property "subject to" the mortgage, the assumption of the mortgage debt by the property
purchaser, and any exchange of possession of the property under a land sales contract or any
other land trust device.
Grantee is a person who acquires an interest in land by deed, grant, or other written instrument.

GNMA (Ginnie May) - Government National Mortgage Association, a government corporation
which provides a secondary market for housing mortgages and special assistance to mortgagee
financing housing under special FHA mortgage insurance programs.

Freddie Mac - Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (also FHLMC) is a stockholder
owned corporation charted by Congress that purchases mortgage loans.
An Assessor is a public official who evaluates property for the purpose of taxation.

An Assignee is one to whom a transfer of interest is made. For example, the assignee of a mortgage
or contract.
An Assignor is one who makes an assignment. For example, the assignor of a mortgage or contract.
An Attachment is one who makes an assignment. For example, the assignor of a mortgage or contract.

An Attorney-in-Fact is one who holds a power of attorney from another allowing him or her to
execute legal documents such as deeds, mortgages, etc., on behalf of the grantor of the power.

An Attorney's Opinion is the written statement of an attorney setting forth what he believes to be
the condition of a real estate title.

Binder is an enforceable agreement that upon satisfaction of the requirements which are stated
in the binder the insurer will issue the specified title insurance policy subject only to the
exceptions stated in the binder.

Broker - Real Estate: One who acts as an agent for another in negotiating sales or purchases in
return for a fee or commission. Mortgage: Refers to a company or individual that does not lend
the money for the loans themselves, but broker loans to larger lenders or investors.

searchable_info.topic: What is Bureau of Land Management?
searchable_info.description:
Bureau of Land Management is the branch of government in charge of surveying and
managing public lands.

searchable_info.topic: What is a Certificate of Title
searchable_info.description:
Certificate of Title is a written opinion by an attorney that ownership of the particular parcel of
land is as stated in the certificate.

Claim is a right to assert, or the assertion of, a demand for payment of money due; or the
surrender or delivery of possession of property or the recognition or some right. A demand for
something as one's rightful due.

Commitment is a promulgated form issued by a title insurance company, or its agent,
committing the title insurance company to issue the form of policy designated in the
commitment upon compliance with and satisfaction of requirements set forth in the commitment.

Common Areas is ownership characterized by mutual ownership of common areas, either
jointly or through membership in an association, e.g., condominiums, planned unit
developments, and townhomes.

Covenant is an agreement written into deeds and other instruments promising performance or
non-performance of certain acts, or stipulating certain uses or non-uses of the property.

Exceptions are those matters affecting title to the particular parcel of realty which matters are
excluded from coverage of the particular title insurance policy.

Examiner is usually referred to, in title industry terms, as title examiner. One who examines and
determines the condition and status of real estate titles.

Examination of Title is the investigation and interpretation of the record title to real property
based on the title search or abstract.
Et Ux =  And wife.
Et Al = And others.

Escheat is the transfer of title of property to the state if the owner dies intestate and without
heirs, or if the owner is unknown or fails to claim property within a set amount of time.

Encumbrance is any right or interest in land held by persons other than the fee owner which
right or interest lessens the value of the fee title. Examples are judgment liens, easements,
mortgages, restrictions.

Encumber is to burden a parcel of land with a lien or charge; e.g., a mortgage.
See: lien

Eminent Domain is the power of the state to take private property for public use upon payment
of just compensation.
Egress is the right to leave a tract of land. Often used interchangeably with "access."

term: how do I contact a county clerk
how do I contact a district clerk

help_info.description: Birth certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain birth certificate contact the County Clerk's office using our county directory below.
Death certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a death certificate contact the County Clerk's office using our county directory below.
Marriage certificates are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a marriage certificate contact the County Clerk's office using our county directory below.

help_info.topic: Looking for information about a Texas Drivers license?
help_info.description: TexasFile does not provide information about drivers licenses. For more information, contact the Texas Department of Public Safety using the link below.
Criminal records are not available on TexasFile. To locate this information contact the District Clerk's office using our county directory below.
TexasFile does not provide access to District Clerk or District Court records. Please contact the District Clerk's office using our county directory below.

help_info.topic: Looking for a copy of your home survey?
help_info.description: Residential home surveys are typically not recorded in the County Clerk office and not available on TexasFile. The title agent that closed your real estate transaction may have a copy of your survey. Use the link below to locate a title agent.

term: how do i change my username
help_info.description: Changing your username requires TexasFile customer support assistance. Please contact us using the link below.
Divorce decrees are not available on TexasFile. To obtain a divorce decree contact the County Clerk's office using our county directory below.
